<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-15T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-15T17:00:00-05:00" n="398" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d398">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A.R.–N.C./100: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-15T18:00:00-04:00">May 15, 1940—6
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>127. Your 217, May 14, 2 p.m. From the Under Secretary for Fenwick. In
                            view of the fact that the Uruguayan Government has already circulated to
                            the other American Republics a proposal for a joint declaration
                            regarding the invasion of Holland, Belgium and Luxemburg,<note n="79" xml:id="d398fn1">See <ref target="frus1940v01#pg_727">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 727</ref> ff.</note> I am sure
                            that you will concur with me as to the disadvantages of duplication in
                            these matters and that you will agree that the Uruguayan proposal takes
                            care of the situation adequately. [Welles.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>